## Description {#details}

This file exposes an interface to building/using memory SSA to walk memory instructions using a use/def graph.

Memory SSA class builds an SSA form that links together memory access instructions such as loads, stores, atomics, and calls. Additionally, it does a trivial form of &quot;heap versioning&quot; Every time the memory state changes in the program, we generate a new heap version. It generates MemoryDef/Uses/Phis that are overlayed on top of the existing instructions.

As a trivial example, define i32 @main() #0 &#123; entry: call = call noalias i8&#42; @&#95;Znwm(i64 4) #2 %0 = bitcast i8&#42; call to i32&#42; call1 = call noalias i8&#42; @&#95;Znwm(i64 4) #2 %1 = bitcast i8&#42; call1 to i32&#42; store i32 5, i32&#42; %0, align 4 store i32 7, i32&#42; %1, align 4 %2 = load i32&#42; %0, align 4 %3 = load i32&#42; %1, align 4 add = add nsw i32 %2, %3 ret i32 add &#125;

Will become define i32 @main() #0 &#123; entry: ; 1 = MemoryDef(0) call = call noalias i8&#42; @&#95;Znwm(i64 4) #3 %2 = bitcast i8&#42; call to i32&#42; ; 2 = MemoryDef(1) call1 = call noalias i8&#42; @&#95;Znwm(i64 4) #3 %4 = bitcast i8&#42; call1 to i32&#42; ; 3 = MemoryDef(2) store i32 5, i32&#42; %2, align 4 ; 4 = MemoryDef(3) store i32 7, i32&#42; %4, align 4 ; MemoryUse(3) %7 = load i32&#42; %2, align 4 ; MemoryUse(4) %8 = load i32&#42; %4, align 4 add = add nsw i32 %7, %8 ret i32 add &#125;

Given this form, all the stores that could ever effect the load at %8 can be gotten by using the MemoryUse associated with it, and walking from use to def until you hit the top of the function.

Each def also has a list of users associated with it, so you can walk from both def to users, and users to defs. Note that we disambiguate MemoryUses, but not the RHS of MemoryDefs. You can see this above at %7, which would otherwise be a MemoryUse(4). Being disambiguated means that for a given store, all the MemoryUses on its use lists are may-aliases of that store (but the MemoryDefs on its use list may not be).

MemoryDefs are not disambiguated because it would require multiple reaching definitions, which would require multiple phis, and multiple memoryaccesses per instruction.

In addition to the def/use graph described above, MemoryDefs also contain an &quot;optimized&quot; definition use. The &quot;optimized&quot; use points to some def reachable through the memory def chain. The optimized def <em>may</em> (but is not required to) alias the original MemoryDef, but no def <em>closer</em> to the source def may alias it. As the name implies, the purpose of the optimized use is to allow caching of clobber searches for memory defs. The optimized def may be nullptr, in which case clients must walk the defining access chain.

When iterating the uses of a MemoryDef, both defining uses and optimized uses will be encountered. If only one type is needed, the client must filter the use walk.

<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><Highlight kind="comment">/// reachable through the memory def chain.  The optimized def &#42;may&#42; (but is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><Highlight kind="comment">/// not required to) alias the original MemoryDef, but no def &#42;closer&#42; to the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><Highlight kind="comment">/// source def may alias it.  As the name implies, the purpose of the optimized</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><Highlight kind="comment">/// use is to allow caching of clobber searches for memory defs.  The optimized</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><Highlight kind="comment">/// def may be nullptr, in which case clients must walk the defining access</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00077" /><CodeLine lineNumber="77"><Highlight kind="comment">/// chain.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00078" /><CodeLine lineNumber="78"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00079" /><CodeLine lineNumber="79"><Highlight kind="comment">/// When iterating the uses of a MemoryDef, both defining uses and optimized</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00080" /><CodeLine lineNumber="80"><Highlight kind="comment">/// uses will be encountered.  If only one type is needed, the client must</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00081" /><CodeLine lineNumber="81"><Highlight kind="comment">/// filter the use walk.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00082" /><CodeLine lineNumber="82"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00083" /><CodeLine lineNumber="83"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00084" /><CodeLine lineNumber="84"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00361" /><CodeLine lineNumber="361"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/// Represents a read-write access to memory, whether it is a must-alias,</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00445" /><CodeLine lineNumber="445"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00446" /><CodeLine lineNumber="446"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/// Represents phi nodes for memory accesses.</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00447" /><CodeLine lineNumber="447"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00448" /><CodeLine lineNumber="448"><Highlight kind="comment">/// These have the same semantic as regular phi nodes, with the exception that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00449" /><CodeLine lineNumber="449"><Highlight kind="comment">/// only one phi will ever exist in a given basic block.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00450" /><CodeLine lineNumber="450"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Guaranteeing one phi per block means guaranteeing there is only ever one</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00451" /><CodeLine lineNumber="451"><Highlight kind="comment">/// valid reaching MemoryDef/MemoryPHI along each path to the phi node.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00452" /><CodeLine lineNumber="452"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is ensured by not allowing disambiguation of the RHS of a MemoryDef or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00453" /><CodeLine lineNumber="453"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a MemoryPhi&#39;s operands.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00454" /><CodeLine lineNumber="454"><Highlight kind="comment">/// That is, given</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00455" /><CodeLine lineNumber="455"><Highlight kind="comment">/// if (a) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00456" /><CodeLine lineNumber="456"><Highlight kind="comment">///   store %a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00457" /><CodeLine lineNumber="457"><Highlight kind="comment">///   store %b</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00458" /><CodeLine lineNumber="458"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00459" /><CodeLine lineNumber="459"><Highlight kind="comment">/// it &#42;must&#42; be transformed into</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00460" /><CodeLine lineNumber="460"><Highlight kind="comment">/// if (a) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00461" /><CodeLine lineNumber="461"><Highlight kind="comment">///    1 = MemoryDef(liveOnEntry)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00462" /><CodeLine lineNumber="462"><Highlight kind="comment">///    store %a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00463" /><CodeLine lineNumber="463"><Highlight kind="comment">///    2 = MemoryDef(1)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00464" /><CodeLine lineNumber="464"><Highlight kind="comment">///    store %b</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00465" /><CodeLine lineNumber="465"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00466" /><CodeLine lineNumber="466"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and &#42;not&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00467" /><CodeLine lineNumber="467"><Highlight kind="comment">/// if (a) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00468" /><CodeLine lineNumber="468"><Highlight kind="comment">///    1 = MemoryDef(liveOnEntry)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00469" /><CodeLine lineNumber="469"><Highlight kind="comment">///    store %a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00470" /><CodeLine lineNumber="470"><Highlight kind="comment">///    2 = MemoryDef(liveOnEntry)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00471" /><CodeLine lineNumber="471"><Highlight kind="comment">///    store %b</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00472" /><CodeLine lineNumber="472"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00473" /><CodeLine lineNumber="473"><Highlight kind="comment">/// even if the two stores do not conflict. Otherwise, both 1 and 2 reach the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00474" /><CodeLine lineNumber="474"><Highlight kind="comment">/// end of the branch, and if there are not two phi nodes, one will be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00475" /><CodeLine lineNumber="475"><Highlight kind="comment">/// disconnected completely from the SSA graph below that point.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00476" /><CodeLine lineNumber="476"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Because MemoryUse&#39;s do not generate new definitions, they do not have this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00477" /><CodeLine lineNumber="477"><Highlight kind="comment">/// issue.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00478" /><CodeLine lineNumber="478" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryphi"><Highlight kind="normal">class <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryphi/#ad97f929f3156780ebc1bb6f35749de92">MemoryPhi</a> final : public <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryaccess/#a1b9eff8c50a34b8b28a26dc74f949fca">MemoryAccess</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01004" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1004"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01005" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1005"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is the generic walker interface for walkers of MemorySSA.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01006" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1006"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Walkers are used to be able to further disambiguate the def-use chains</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01007" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1007"><Highlight kind="comment">/// MemorySSA gives you, or otherwise produce better info than MemorySSA gives</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01008" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1008"><Highlight kind="comment">/// you.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1009"><Highlight kind="comment">/// In particular, while the def-use chains provide basic information, and are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1010"><Highlight kind="comment">/// guaranteed to give, for example, the nearest may-aliasing MemoryDef for a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1011"><Highlight kind="comment">/// MemoryUse as AliasAnalysis considers it, a user mant want better or other</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1012"><Highlight kind="comment">/// information. In particular, they may want to use SCEV info to further</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1013"><Highlight kind="comment">/// disambiguate memory accesses, or they may want the nearest dominating</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1014"><Highlight kind="comment">/// may-aliasing MemoryDef for a call or a store. This API enables a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1015"><Highlight kind="comment">/// standardized interface to getting and using that info.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1016" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a3cda9987d773268f1db499ac10de10f3">MemorySSAWalker</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1017"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1018"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a3cda9987d773268f1db499ac10de10f3">MemorySSAWalker</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a049277aa22bd6d1efded38d340c37960">MemorySSA</a> &#42;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1019" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a6d37dfce50a3a6f2f6f7ba75107feba7"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">virtual</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a6d37dfce50a3a6f2f6f7ba75107feba7">~MemorySSAWalker</a>() = </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">default</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1020"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01021" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1021" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a039ffa93cf728edc3399834d754a4a72"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">using </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memoryssawalker/#a039ffa93cf728edc3399834d754a4a72">MemoryAccessSet</a> = <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/smallvector">SmallVector&lt;MemoryAccess &#42;, 8&gt;</a>;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01022" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1022"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1023"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Given a memory Mod/Ref/ModRef&#39;ing instruction, calling this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1024"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// will give you the nearest dominating MemoryAccess that Mod&#39;s the location</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1025"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// the instruction accesses (by skipping any def which AA can prove does not</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1026"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// alias the location(s) accessed by the instruction given).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1027"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1028"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Note that this will return a single access, and it must dominate the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1029"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Instruction, so if an operand of a MemoryPhi node Mod&#39;s the instruction,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1030"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// this will return the MemoryPhi, not the operand. This means that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1031"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// given:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1032"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// if (a) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1033"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   1 = MemoryDef(liveOnEntry)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1034"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   store %a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1035"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// &#125; else &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1036"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   2 = MemoryDef(liveOnEntry)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1037"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   store %b</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1038"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1039"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 3 = MemoryPhi(2, 1)</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01310" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1310"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01311" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1311"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Walks the defining accesses of MemoryDefs. Stops after we hit something that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01312" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1312"><Highlight kind="comment">/// has no defining use (e.g. a MemoryPhi or liveOnEntry). Note that, when</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01313" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1313"><Highlight kind="comment">/// comparing against a null def&#95;chain&#95;iterator, this will compare equal only</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01314" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1314"><Highlight kind="comment">/// after walking said Phi/liveOnEntry.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01315" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1315"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01316" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1316"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The UseOptimizedChain flag specifies whether to walk the clobbering</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01317" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1317"><Highlight kind="comment">/// access chain, or all the accesses.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01318" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1318"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01319" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1319"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Normally, MemoryDef are all just def/use linked together, so a def&#95;chain on</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01320" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1320"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a MemoryDef will walk all MemoryDefs above it in the program until it hits</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01321" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1321"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a phi node.  The optimized chain walks the clobbering access of a store.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01322" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1322"><Highlight kind="comment">/// So if you are just trying to find, given a store, what the next</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01323" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1323"><Highlight kind="comment">/// thing that would clobber the same memory is, you want the optimized chain.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
